english:
  title: Record of the New Construction of Huiyin Temple
  author: Kim Bu-sik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Some twenty li south of Bongseong County stood a small temple, long fallen to ruin, yet the local people still called that place Stone Temple Valley. All who traveled from the southeastern provinces to the capital, or descended from the upper regions, had to pass through here. Shoulders brushed together, hoofprints overlapped—the traffic never ceased. But the mountain slopes lay deep and distant, the undergrowth thick and tangled. Tigers prowled in packs, treating it as a haven, lurking in shadow, watching sidelong, emerging at times to wreak havoc. Nor was this the only danger. Brigands and bandits found the desolate terrain perfect for hiding, travelers easy prey for their fear. Here they came, here they nested, plying their wickedness. Those passing to and fro hesitated, dared not advance alone. They warned each other to travel in large groups, bearing weapons to pass safely—yet still, hundreds perished each year.

    In the fifteenth year of King Yejong's reign, in the eighth month of the year Kihai, the trusted minister Socheon returned from a journey south on royal business. The king asked, "Have you heard of the people's suffering on your travels?" Socheon reported the calamity. The king, moved to compassion, asked, "How can we end this harm and bring peace to the people?"

    Socheon replied, "If Your Majesty will hear my counsel, I have a plan that costs the treasury nothing and burdens the people not at all. Let us gather monks to rebuild that ruined temple and gather the righteous there. Let us build dwellings nearby and settle wandering folk. Then beasts and brigands will naturally depart, and the roads will know peace."

    The king said, "Good. See that it is done."

    Socheon then traveled to Myohyang Temple and announced to the assembly: "A great danger afflicts a certain place. The realm cannot impose construction upon the people to remedy it. In former times, the masters saw suffering and gave fearless aid. Who among you will follow me to that place and undertake this work?"

    The abbot Hyegwan gladly consented, and a hundred of his monks offered to go. Though aged and unable to travel himself, Hyegwan selected sixteen capable and diligent practitioners, including Jeungyeo, provided them provisions, and sent them forth. By the eleventh month of winter, they arrived and built temporary shelters.

    The king appointed the monk Eungje to oversee the work, with his disciple Mincheong as assistant. In the spring of the year Gyeongja, in the second month, construction began. By the spring of the second month of the year Imyin, the work was complete. There arose a meditation hall, a dwelling for repose, kitchens, and storehouses—all properly appointed. Foreseeing that the royal carriage might someday journey south and rest here, they further built a separate guest pavilion, elegant and splendid to behold.

    When the present king took the throne, he granted the temple the name Huiyin. Behold how deep forest became a sanctuary, how a road of fear became a path of peace! Is not the benefit boundless?

    They established granaries and distributed their produce, setting up gruel to sustain travelers—a practice nearly abandoned now. Socheon wished this to continue without end. His sincerity moved donors, and benefactions came forth. The king, hearing this, gave generously. Queen Imshi too, upon learning of it, rejoiced and said, "All these works shall have my patronage." She replenished the failing stores and replaced worn implements, so that nothing remained lacking.

    Some asked: "The sage Mencius tells how in Yao's time, when floods raged, Yu was sent to tame them, and creatures that harmed mankind vanished, so people could dwell in peace. Or how Yi burned the mountains and marshes, and beasts fled and hid. When Duke Zhou assisted King Wu, driving tigers, leopards, rhinoceroses, and elephants far away, the world rejoiced. In the Spring and Autumn period, when bandits infested the lands of Zheng, taking people from the marshes, Dachun ended them. In the Han, when the Bohai region starved and rebellion stirred, Gongsu restored order. Throughout history, none lack deeds of suppressing bandits recorded in the chronicles. So ridding the land of beasts and brigands is the duty of princes and ministers. Yet Socheon is but a minor official, and Eungje and Mincheong are merely monks—is this not overreach? Can such a deed merit recording for posterity?"

    "Moreover, the Buddha teaches that giving is noblest when done without attachment. Zhuangzi too said that a gift forgotten is a true gift. Why inscribe so small an act of kindness?"

    I respond: "Not so. In the late years of Tang's Zhenyuan era, when a great flood swept mankind and goods eastward like scattered wood, a certain monk took pity and rescued the drowning, restoring hundreds to life—Liu Mengde recorded this. In Song's Xining period, when Chen Shugu governed Hangzhou and asked of the people's needs, all spoke of six wells fallen into disrepair, leaving them without water. He ordered monks Zhongwen and Zikui to restore them—Su Zhe recorded this. Does not the gentleman take joy in praising virtue thus? How can we remain silent?

    Yet while it is noble for one to do good and forget it, without one to transmit the deed, how shall virtue be encouraged? Even in the Buddhist sutras and scriptures, such deeds are recounted. The monk Daibing of Tang established eight successive feasts of giving—these Tonghuei recorded in the monastic chronicles. Even Confucian texts contain such examples. The Record of Rites tells how the nobleman Gongshu Wenzi made gruel for the starving of his state—was this not benevolence? Such deeds must indeed be recorded.

    Socheon bears the surname Lee. His father, Lee Sung, was skilled in writing, passed the civil service examination, and rose to the posts of Left Censor and Director of the Imperial Secretariat before his death. Socheon himself reached the seventh rank. In hours free from duty, he served the Buddha with utmost reverence. Now he wears rough hemp robes, eats only vegetables, and calls himself a lay disciple, practicing with diligence. For this the king came to know him, and thus he accomplished these great works.

    Eungje held the position but briefly; Mincheong succeeded him and brought the work to completion—truly capable. All resources came from royal grants and the offerings of believers, their names listed in the supplementary records below.

    Written in the spring, second month, of the year Gapja.
  footnotes:
    - 'Socheon (少千): A trusted minister of King Yejong, known for his administrative ability and religious devotion.'
    - 'Myohyang Temple (妙香山): One of Korea''s most important Buddhist temples, located in the Diamond Mountains region.'
    - The structural transformation from wilderness to sanctuary represents both practical reform and spiritual renewal in Goryeo society.
    - The classical Chinese parallels cited (Yu controlling floods, Duke Zhou's campaigns) connect this work to Confucian concepts of virtuous rulership.
    - The gruel distribution project represents an early form of social welfare in medieval Korea.
    - Kim Bu-sik (1075-1151) was a renowned Goryeo historian and statesman, author of the Samguk Sagi (History of the Three Kingdoms).
